# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-fsx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-fsx/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates systems administration (including network and security knowledge), parallel computing and distributed computing into a multidisciplinary field that combines digital electronics, computer architecture, system software, programming languages, algorithms and computational techniques.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] HPC technologies are the tools and systems used to implement and create high performance computing systems.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Since around 2005, HPC systems have shifted from supercomputing to computing clusters and grids.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Because of the need of networking in clusters and grids, High Performance Computing Technologies are achieved by the use of a collapsed network backbone, because the collapsed backbone architecture is simple to troubleshoot and upgrades can be applied to a single router as opposed to multiple ones.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates with data analytics in AI engineering workflows to generate new data streams that increase a simulation's ability to answer the "what if" questions.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] The term is most commonly associated with computing used for scientific research or computational science.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] A related term, high-performance technical computing (HPTC), generally refers to the engineering applications of cluster-based computing (such as computational fluid dynamics and the building and testing of virtual prototypes).
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] HPC has also been applied to business uses such as data warehouses, line of business (LOB) applications, and transaction processing.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] High-performance computing (HPC) as a term arose after the term "supercomputing".
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] HPC is sometimes used as a synonym for supercomputing; but, in other contexts, "supercomputer" is used to refer to a more powerful subset of "high-performance computers", and the term "supercomputing" becomes a subset of "high-performance computing".
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] The potential for confusion over the use of these terms is apparent.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Because most current applications are not designed for HPC technologies but are retrofitted, they are not designed or tested for scaling to more powerful processors or machines.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Since networking clusters and grids use multiple processors and computers, these scaling problems can cripple critical systems in future supercomputing systems.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Therefore, either the existing tools do not address the needs of the high performance computing community or the HPC community is unaware of these tools.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] In government and research institutions, scientists simulate galaxy formation and evolution, fusion energy, and global warming, as well as work to create more accurate short- and long-term weather forecasts.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] The world's tenth most powerful supercomputer in 2008, IBM Roadrunner (located at the United States Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory) simulated the performance, safety, and reliability of nuclear weapons and certifies their functionality.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] TOP500 ranks the world's 500 fastest high-performance computers, as measured by the High Performance LINPACK (HPL) benchmark.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Not all existing computers are ranked, either because they are ineligible (e.g., they cannot run the HPL benchmark) or because their owners have not submitted an HPL score (e.g., because they do not wish the size of their system to become public information, for defense reasons).
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] In addition, the use of the single LINPACK benchmark is controversial, in that no single measure can test all aspects of a high-performance computer.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] To help overcome the limitations of the LINPACK test, the U.S. government commissioned one of its originators, Jack Dongarra of the University of Tennessee, to create a suite of benchmark tests that includes LINPACK and others, called the HPC Challenge benchmark suite.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] This evolving suite has been used in some HPC procurements, but, because it is not reducible to a single number, it has been unable to overcome the publicity advantage of the less useful TOP500 LINPACK test.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] The TOP500 list is updated twice a year, once in June at the ISC European Supercomputing Conference and again at a US Supercomputing Conference in November.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Many ideas for the new wave of grid computing were originally borrowed from HPC.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Traditionally, HPC has involved an on-premises infrastructure, investing in supercomputers or computer clusters.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Over the last decade, cloud computing has grown in popularity for offering computer resources in the commercial sector regardless of their investment capabilities.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] Some characteristics like scalability and containerization also have raised interest in academia.
[src:aws-fsx/high-performance-computing] However security in the cloud concerns such as data confidentiality are still considered when deciding between cloud or on-premise HPC resources.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A NAS device is optimised for serving files either by its hardware, software, or configuration.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] It is often manufactured as a computer appliance – a purpose-built specialized computer.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS systems are networked appliances that contain one or more storage drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Network-attached storage typically provide access to files using network file sharing protocols such as NFS, SMB, or AFP.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Accompanying a NAS are purpose-built hard disk drives, which are functionally similar to non-NAS drives but may have different firmware, vibration tolerance, or power dissipation to make them more suitable for use in RAID arrays, a technology often used in NAS implementations.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] For example, some NAS versions of drives support a command extension to allow extended error recovery to be disabled.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] In a non-RAID application, it may be important for a disk drive to go to great lengths to successfully read a problematic storage block, even if it takes several seconds.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] In an appropriately configured RAID array, a single bad block on a single drive can be recovered completely via the redundancy encoded across the RAID set.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A NAS unit is a computer connected to a network that provides only file-based data storage services to other devices on the network.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Although it may technically be possible to run other software on a NAS unit, it is usually not designed to be a general-purpose server.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] For example, NAS units usually do not have a keyboard or display, and are controlled and configured over the network, often using a browser.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A full-featured operating system is not needed on a NAS device, so often a stripped-down operating system is used.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS systems contain one or more hard disk drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS uses file-based protocols such as NFS (popular on UNIX systems), SMB (Server Message Block) (used with Microsoft Windows systems), AFP (used with Apple Macintosh computers), or NCP (used with OES and Novell NetWare).
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS units rarely limit clients to a single protocol.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The key difference between direct-attached storage (DAS) and NAS is that DAS is simply an extension to an existing server and is not necessarily networked.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] As the name suggests, DAS typically is connected via a USB or Thunderbolt enabled cable.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS is designed as an easy and self-contained solution for sharing files over the network.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Both DAS and NAS can potentially increase availability of data by using RAID or clustering.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Both NAS and DAS can have various amount of cache memory, which greatly affects performance.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] When comparing use of NAS with use of local (non-networked) DAS, the performance of NAS depends mainly on the speed of and congestion on the network.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Most NAS solutions will include the option to install a wide array of software applications to allow better configuration of the system or to include other capabilities outside of storage (like video surveillance, virtualization, media, etc).
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] DAS typically is focused solely on data storage but capabilities can be available based on specific vendor options.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS provides both storage and a file system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] This is often contrasted with SAN (storage area network), which provides only block-based storage and leaves file system concerns on the "client" side.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] SAN protocols include Fibre Channel, iSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE) and HyperSCSI.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Despite their differences, SAN and NAS are not mutually exclusive and may be combined as a SAN-NAS hybrid, offering both file-level protocols (NAS) and block-level protocols (SAN) from the same system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A shared disk file system can also be run on top of a SAN to provide filesystem services.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] In the early 1980s, the "Newcastle Connection" by Brian Randell and his colleagues at Newcastle University demonstrated and developed remote file access across a set of UNIX machines.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Novell's NetWare server operating system and NCP protocol was released in 1983.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Following the Newcastle Connection, Sun Microsystems' 1984 release of NFS allowed network servers to share their storage space with networked clients.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] 3Com and Microsoft would develop the LAN Manager software and protocol to further this new market.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] 3Com's 3Server and 3+Share software was the first purpose-built server (including proprietary hardware, software, and multiple disks) for open systems servers.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Inspired by the success of file servers from Novell, IBM, and Sun, several firms developed dedicated file servers.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] While 3Com was among the first firms to build a dedicated NAS for desktop operating systems, Auspex Systems was one of the first to develop a dedicated NFS server for use in the UNIX market.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A group of Auspex engineers split away in the early 1990s to create the integrated NetApp FAS, which supported both the Windows SMB and the UNIX NFS protocols and had superior scalability and ease of deployment.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] This started the market for proprietary NAS devices now led by NetApp and EMC Celerra.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] In 2009, NAS vendors (notably CTERA networks and Netgear) began to introduce online backup solutions integrated in their NAS appliances, for online disaster recovery.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] By 2021, three major types of NAS solutions are offered (all with hybrid cloud models where data can be stored both on-premise on the NAS and off site on a separate NAS or through a public cloud service provider).
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The first type of NAS is focused on consumer needs with lower-cost options that typically support 1–5 hot plug hard drives.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The second is focused on small-to-medium-sized businesses – these NAS solutions range from 2–24+ hard drives and are typically offered in tower or rackmount form factors.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Pricing can vary greatly depending on the processor, components, and overall features supported.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The last type is geared toward enterprises or large businesses and are offered with more advanced software capabilities.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS solutions are typically sold without hard drives installed to allow the buyer (or IT departments) to select the hard drive cost, size, and quality.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Embedded-system-based NAS – using an ARM- or MIPS-based processor architecture and a real-time operating system (RTOS) or an embedded operating system to run a NAS server.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this NAS type is fair, and functions in the NAS can fit most end-user requirements.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Marvell, Oxford, and Storlink make chipsets for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Max FTP throughput varies from 20 MB/s to 120 MB/s.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] ASIC-based NAS – provisioning NAS through the use of a single ASIC chip, using hardware to implement TCP/IP and file system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] There is no OS in the chip, as all the performance-related operations are done by hardware acceleration circuits.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this type of NAS is low, as functions are limited to only support SMB and FTP.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] LayerWalker is the only chipset manufacturer for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS is useful for more than just general centralized storage provided to client computers in environments with large amounts of data.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] NAS can enable simpler and lower cost systems such as load-balancing and fault-tolerant email and web server systems by providing storage services.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] In the consumer market, NAS devices have evolved into "private cloud" solutions.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] They allow users to store multimedia data and back up files from various devices (such as smartphones and PCs) while retaining full data ownership.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Unlike public cloud services, these private cloud setups typically do not require monthly subscription fees for storage capacity.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Such consumer market appliances are now commonly available.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Unlike their rackmounted counterparts, they are generally packaged in smaller form factors.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The price of NAS appliances has fallen sharply in recent years, offering flexible network-based storage to the home consumer market for little more than the cost of a regular USB or FireWire external hard disk.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Many of these home consumer devices are built around ARM, x86 or MIPS processors running an embedded Linux operating system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A **purpose-built backup appliance** (PBBA) is a kind of NAS intended for storing backup data.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] PBBAs typically include data deduplication, compression, RAID 6 or other redundant hardware components, and automated maintenance.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A PBBA may also be called a **backup and disaster recovery appliance** or simply a **backup appliance**.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Open-source NAS-oriented distributions of Linux and FreeBSD are available.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] These are designed to be easy to set up on commodity PC hardware, and are typically configured using a web browser.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] They can run from a virtual machine, Live CD, bootable USB flash drive (Live USB), or from one of the mounted hard drives.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] They run Samba (an SMB daemon), NFS daemon, and FTP daemons which are freely available for those operating systems.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] If the client can be granted access to the file requested, the client receives the network location of NASD disks and their capability.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] If the client is accessing the disk for the first time, it receives a time-limited key for the establishment of secure communication to the disk.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The file manager informs the corresponding disk using an independent channel.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] From now on, the client directly accesses the NASD disks by giving the capability it received and further data transfers go through the network, bypassing the file manager.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] A **clustered NAS** is a NAS that is using a distributed file system running simultaneously on multiple servers.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] The key difference between a clustered and traditional NAS is the ability to distribute (e.g. stripe) data and metadata across the cluster nodes or storage devices.
[src:aws-fsx/network-attached-storage] Clustered NAS, like a traditional one, still provides unified access to the files from any of the cluster nodes, unrelated to the actual location of the data.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] A **clustered file system** (**CFS**) is a file system which is shared by being simultaneously mounted on multiple servers.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] There are several approaches to clustering, most of which do not employ a clustered file system (only direct attached storage for each node).
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Clustered file systems can provide features like location-independent addressing and redundancy which improve reliability or reduce the complexity of the other parts of the cluster.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] **Parallel file systems** are a type of clustered file system that spread data across multiple storage nodes, usually for redundancy or performance.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] A **shared-disk file system** uses a storage area network (SAN) to allow multiple computers to gain direct disk access at the block level.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Access control and translation from file-level operations that applications use to block-level operations used by the SAN must take place on the client node.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Shared-disk file-systems commonly employ some sort of fencing mechanism to prevent data corruption in case of node failures, because an unfenced device can cause data corruption if it loses communication with its sister nodes and tries to access the same information other nodes are accessing.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] The underlying storage area network may use any of a number of block-level protocols, including SCSI, iSCSI, HyperSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE), Fibre Channel, network block device, and InfiniBand.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] There are different architectural approaches to a shared-disk filesystem.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Some distribute file information across all the servers in a cluster (fully distributed).
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Distributed data stores, by contrast, require using a different API or library and have different semantics (most often those of a database).
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Distributed file systems may aim for "transparency" in a number of aspects.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] That is, they aim to be "invisible" to client programs, which "see" a system which is similar to a local file system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Behind the scenes, the distributed file system handles locating files, transporting data, and potentially providing other features listed below.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] The Incompatible Timesharing System used virtual devices for transparent inter-machine file system access in the 1960s.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] More file servers were developed in the 1970s.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] In 1976, Digital Equipment Corporation created the File Access Listener (FAL), an implementation of the Data Access Protocol as part of DECnet Phase II which became the first widely used network file system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] In 1984, Sun Microsystems created the file system called "Network File System" (NFS) which became the first widely used Internet Protocol based network file system.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Other notable network file systems are Andrew File System (AFS), Apple Filing Protocol (AFP), NetWare Core Protocol (NCP), and Server Message Block (SMB) which is also known as Common Internet File System (CIFS).
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] In 1986, IBM announced client and server support for Distributed Data Management Architecture (DDM) for the System/36, System/38, and IBM mainframe computers running CICS.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] This was followed by the support for IBM Personal Computer, AS/400, IBM mainframe computers under the MVS and VSE operating systems, and FlexOS.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] DDM also became the foundation for Distributed Relational Database Architecture, also known as DRDA.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] There are many peer-to-peer network protocols for open-source distributed file systems for cloud or closed-source clustered file systems, e. g.: 9P, AFS, Coda, CIFS/SMB, DCE/DFS, WekaFS, Lustre, PanFS, Google File System, Mnet, Chord Project.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Network-attached storage (NAS) provides both storage and a file system, like a shared disk file system on top of a storage area network (SAN).
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] The failure of disk hardware or a given storage node in a cluster can create a single point of failure that can result in data loss or unavailability.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Fault tolerance and high availability can be provided through data replication of one sort or another, so that data remains intact and available despite the failure of any single piece of equipment.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] For examples, see the lists of distributed fault-tolerant file systems and distributed parallel fault-tolerant file systems.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] A common performance measurement of a clustered file system is the amount of time needed to satisfy service requests.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] In conventional systems, this time consists of a disk-access time and a small amount of CPU-processing time.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] But in a clustered file system, a remote access has additional overhead due to the distributed structure.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] This includes the time to deliver the request to a server, the time to deliver the response to the client, and for each direction, a CPU overhead of running the communication protocol software.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Concurrency control becomes an issue when more than one person or client is accessing the same file or block and want to update it.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] Hence updates to the file from one client should not interfere with access and updates from other clients.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] This problem is more complex with file systems due to concurrent overlapping writes, where different writers write to overlapping regions of the file concurrently.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] This problem is usually handled by concurrency control or locking which may either be built into the file system or provided by an add-on protocol.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] IBM mainframes in the 1970s could share physical disks and file systems if each machine had its own channel connection to the drives' control units.
[src:aws-fsx/network-file-system] In the 1980s, Digital Equipment Corporation's TOPS-20 and OpenVMS clusters (VAX/ALPHA/IA64) included shared disk file systems.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB was originally developed in 1983 by Barry A.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Feigenbaum at IBM to share access to files and printers across a network of systems running IBM PC DOS.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] In 1987, Microsoft and 3Com implemented SMB in LAN Manager for OS/2, at which time SMB used the NetBIOS service atop the NetBIOS Frames protocol as its underlying transport.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Later, Microsoft implemented SMB in Windows NT 3.1 and has been updating it ever since, adapting it to work with newer underlying transports: TCP/IP and NetBT.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB over QUIC was introduced in Windows Server 2022.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] In 1996, Microsoft published a version of SMB 1.0 with minor modifications under the **Common Internet File System** (**CIFS** /sɪfs/) moniker.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] CIFS was compatible with even the earliest incarnation of SMB, including LAN Manager's.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It supports symbolic links, hard links, and larger file size, but none of the features of SMB 2.0 and later.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft's proposal, however, remained an Internet Draft and never achieved standard status.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft has since discontinued the CIFS moniker but continues developing SMB and publishing subsequent specifications.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Samba is a free software reimplementation of the SMB protocol and the Microsoft extensions to it.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Server Message Block (SMB) enables file sharing, printer sharing, network browsing, and inter-process communication (through named pipes) over a computer network.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB serves as the basis for Microsoft's Distributed File System implementation.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB relies on the TCP and IP protocols for transport.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This combination allows file sharing over complex, interconnected networks, including the public Internet.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The SMB server component uses TCP port 445.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB originally operated on NetBIOS over IEEE 802.2 - NetBIOS Frames or NBF - and over IPX/SPX, and later on NetBIOS over TCP/IP (NetBT), but Microsoft has since deprecated these protocols.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] On NetBT, the server component uses three TCP or UDP ports: 137 (NETBIOS Name Service), 138 (NETBIOS Datagram Service), and 139 (NETBIOS Session Service).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] In Microsoft Windows, two Windows services implement SMB.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The "Server" service (ID: `LanmanServer`) is in charge of serving shared resources.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The "Workstation" service (ID: `LanmanWorkstation`) maintains the computer name and helps access shared resources on other computers.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB uses the Kerberos protocol to authenticate users against Active Directory on Windows domain networks.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] On simpler, peer-to-peer networks, SMB uses the NTLM protocol.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Windows NT 4.0 SP3 and later can digitally sign SMB messages to prevent some man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB signing may be configured individually for incoming SMB connections (by the "LanmanServer" service) and outgoing SMB connections (by the "LanmanWorkstation" service).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The default setting for Windows domain controllers running Windows Server 2003 and later is to not allow unsigned incoming connections.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] As such, earlier versions of Windows that do not support SMB signing from the get-go (including Windows 9x) cannot connect to a Windows Server 2003 domain controller.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB supports opportunistic locking (see below) on files in order to improve performance.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Opportunistic locking support has changed with each Windows Server release.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] In the SMB protocol, opportunistic locking is a mechanism designed to improve performance by controlling caching of network files by the client.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Unlike traditional locks, opportunistic lock (OpLocks) are not strictly file locking or used to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] There are four types of opportunistic locks.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Batch OpLocks were created originally to support a particular behavior of DOS batch file execution operation in which the file is opened and closed many times in a short period, which is a performance problem.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] To solve this, a client may ask for an OpLock of type "batch".
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] In this case, the client delays sending the close request and if a subsequent open request is given, the two requests cancel each other.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This means that the client may now assume that it is the only process with access to this particular file, and the client may now cache all changes to the file before committing it to the server.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This is a performance improvement, since fewer round-trips are required in order to read and write to the file.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] ) which invalidates the exclusive lock previously given to the client.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The client then flushes all changes to the file.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] If an exclusive OpLock is held by a client and a locked file is opened by a third party, the client has to relinquish its exclusive OpLock to allow the other client's write/read access.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] A client may then receive a "Level 2 OpLock" from the server.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] A Level 2 OpLock allows the caching of read requests but excludes write caching.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Added in Windows NT 4.0, Filter Oplocks are similar to Level 2 OpLocks but prevent sharing-mode violations between file open and lock reception.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft advises use of Filter OpLocks only where it is important to allow multiple readers and Level 2 OpLocks in other circumstances.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] when another client wants to access the file in a way inconsistent with their lock.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The other client's request is held up while the break is being processed.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It informs the client that an OpLock is no longer valid.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This happens, for example, when another client wishes to open a file in a way that invalidates the OpLock.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The first client is then sent an OpLock break and required to send all its local changes (in case of batch or exclusive OpLocks), if any, and acknowledge the OpLock break.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Upon this acknowledgment the server can reply to the second client in a consistent manner.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The use of the SMB protocol has often correlated with a significant increase in broadcast traffic on a network.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] However the SMB itself does not use broadcasts—the broadcast problems commonly associated with SMB actually originate with the NetBIOS service location protocol.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] By default, a Microsoft Windows NT 4.0 server used NetBIOS to advertise and locate services.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] NetBIOS functions by broadcasting services available on a particular host at regular intervals.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] While this usually makes for an acceptable default in a network with a smaller number of hosts, increased broadcast traffic can cause problems as the number of hosts on the network increases.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The implementation of name resolution infrastructure in the form of Windows Internet Naming Service (WINS) or Domain Name System (DNS) resolves this problem.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] WINS was a proprietary implementation used with Windows NT 4.0 networks, but brought about its own issues and complexities in the design and maintenance of a Microsoft network.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Since the release of Windows 2000, the use of WINS for name resolution has been deprecated by Microsoft, with hierarchical Dynamic DNS now configured as the default name resolution protocol for all Windows operating systems.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Resolution of (short) NetBIOS names by DNS requires that a DNS client expand short names, usually by appending a connection-specific DNS suffix to its DNS lookup queries.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] WINS can still be configured on clients as a secondary name resolution protocol for interoperability with legacy Windows environments and applications.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Further, Microsoft DNS servers can forward name resolution requests to legacy WINS servers in order to support name resolution integration with legacy (pre-Windows 2000) environments that do not support DNS.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Network designers have found that latency has a significant impact on the performance of the SMB 1.0 protocol, that it performs more poorly than other protocols like FTP.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Monitoring reveals a high degree of "chattiness" and a disregard of network latency between hosts.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] For example, a VPN connection over the Internet will often introduce network latency.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Solutions to this problem include the updated SMB 2.0 protocol, Offline Files, TCP window scaling and WAN optimization devices from various network vendors that cache and optimize SMB 1.0 and 2.0.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Barry Feigenbaum originally designed SMB at IBM in early 1983 with the aim of turning DOS INT 21h local file access into a networked file system.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft made considerable modifications to the most commonly used version and included SMB support in the LAN Manager operating system it had started developing for OS/2 with 3Com around 1990.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft continued to add features to the protocol in Windows for Workgroups (c.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] LAN Manager authentication was implemented based on the original legacy SMB specification's requirement to use IBM "LAN Manager" passwords, but implemented DES in a flawed manner that allowed passwords to be cracked.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Later, Kerberos authentication was also added.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The Windows domain logon protocols initially used 40-bit encryption outside of the United States, because of export restrictions on stronger 128-bit encryption (subsequently lifted in 1996 when President Bill Clinton signed Executive Order 13026).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB 1.0 (or SMB1) was originally designed to run on NetBIOS Frames (NetBIOS over IEEE 802.2).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Since then, it has been adapted to NetBIOS over IPX/SPX (NBX), and NetBIOS over TCP/IP (NetBT).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Also, since Windows 2000, SMB runs on TCP using TCP port 445, a feature known as "direct host SMB".
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] There is still a thin layer (similar to the Session Message packet of NetBT's Session Service) between SMB and TCP.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Windows Server 2003, and legacy NAS devices use SMB1 natively.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB1 is an extremely chatty protocol, which is not such an issue on a local area network (LAN) with low latency.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It becomes very slow on wide area networks (WAN) as the back and forth handshake of the protocol magnifies the inherent high latency of such a network.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Later versions of the protocol reduced the high number of handshake exchanges.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] One approach to mitigating the inefficiencies in the protocol is to use WAN optimization products such as those provided by Riverbed, Silver Peak, or Cisco.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] A better approach is to upgrade to a later version of SMB.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This includes upgrading both NAS devices as well as Windows Server 2003.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The most effective method to identify SMB1 traffic is with a network analyzer tool, such as Wireshark.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft also provides an auditing tool in Windows Server 2016 to track down devices that use SMB1.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft marked SMB1 as deprecated in June 2013.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Windows Server 2016 and Windows 10 version 1709 do not have SMB1 installed by default.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft submitted some partial specifications as Internet Drafts to the IETF.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft introduced a new version of the protocol (SMB 2.0 or SMB2) in 2006 with Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Although the protocol is proprietary, its specification has been published to allow other systems to interoperate with Microsoft operating systems that use the new protocol.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB2 reduces the 'chattiness' of the SMB 1.0 protocol by reducing the number of commands and subcommands from over a hundred to just nineteen.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It has mechanisms for pipelining, that is, sending additional requests before the response to a previous request arrives, thereby improving performance over high-latency links.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It adds the ability to compound multiple actions into a single request, which significantly reduces the number of round-trips the client needs to make to the server, improving performance as a result.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB1 also has a compounding mechanism—known as AndX—to compound multiple actions, but Microsoft clients rarely use AndX.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It also introduces the notion of "durable file handles": these allow a connection to an SMB server to survive brief network outages, as are typical in a wireless network, without having to incur the overhead of re-negotiating a new session.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB2 includes support for symbolic links.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Other improvements include caching of file properties, improved message signing with HMAC SHA-256 hashing algorithm and better scalability by increasing the number of users, shares and open files per server among others.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The SMB1 protocol uses 16-bit data sizes, which amongst other things, limits the maximum block size to 64K.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB2 uses 32- or 64-bit wide storage fields, and 128 bits in the case of file-handles, thereby removing previous constraints on block sizes, which improves performance with large file transfers over fast networks.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Windows Vista/Server 2008 and later operating systems use SMB2 when communicating with other machines also capable of using SMB2.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB1 continues in use for connections with older versions of Windows, as well various vendors' NAS solutions.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Samba 3.5 also includes experimental support for SMB2.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Samba 3.6 fully supports SMB2, except the modification of user quotas using the Windows quota management tools.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] When SMB2 was introduced it brought a number of benefits over SMB1 for third party implementers of SMB protocols.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB1, originally designed by IBM, was reverse engineered, and later became part of a wide variety of non-Windows operating systems such as Xenix, OS/2 and VMS (Pathworks).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] X/Open standardized it partially; Microsoft had submitted Internet-Drafts describing SMB2 to the IETF, partly in response to formal IETF standardization of version 4 of the Network File System in December 2000.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] However, those SMB-related Internet-Drafts expired without achieving any IETF standards-track approval or any other IETF endorsement.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] (See http://ubiqx.org/cifs/Intro.html for historical detail.) SMB2 is also a relatively clean break with the past.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Microsoft's SMB1 code has to work with a large variety of SMB clients and servers.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB1 features many versions of information for commands (selecting what structure to return for a particular request) because features such as Unicode support were retro-fitted at a later date.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB2 involves significantly reduced compatibility-testing for implementers of the protocol.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB2 code has considerably less complexity since far less variability exists (for example, non-Unicode code paths become redundant as SMB2 requires Unicode support).
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Apple migrated to SMB2 (from their own Apple Filing Protocol, now legacy) starting with OS X 10.9 "Mavericks".
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This transition was fraught with compatibility problems though.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Non-default support for SMB2 appeared in fact in OS X 10.7, when Apple abandoned Samba in favor of its own SMB implementation called SMBX after Samba adopted GPLv3.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The Linux kernel's CIFS client file system has SMB2 support since version 3.7.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB 2.1, introduced with Windows 7 and Server 2008 R2, introduced minor performance enhancements with a new opportunistic locking mechanism.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB 3.0 (previously named SMB 2.2) was introduced with Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It also introduces several security enhancements, such as end-to-end encryption and a new AES based signing algorithm.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB 3.0.2 (known as 3.02 at the time) was introduced with Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2; in those and later releases, the earlier SMB version 1 can be optionally disabled to increase security.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB 3.1.1 was introduced with Windows 10 and Windows Server 2016.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This version supports AES-128 GCM encryption in addition to AES-128 CCM encryption added in SMB3, and implements pre-authentication integrity check using SHA-512 hash.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] SMB 3.1.1 also makes secure negotiation mandatory when connecting to clients using SMB versions that support it.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The specifications for the SMB are proprietary and were initially closed, thereby forcing other vendors and projects to reverse-engineer the protocol to interoperate with it.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The SMB 1.0 protocol was eventually published some time after it was reverse engineered, whereas the SMB 2.0 protocol was made available from Microsoft's Open Specifications Developer Center from the outset.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] As of version 3 (2003), Samba provides file and print services for Microsoft Windows clients and can integrate with a Windows NT 4.0 server domain, either as a Primary Domain Controller (PDC) or as a domain member.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Samba4 installations can act as an Active Directory domain controller or member server, at Windows 2008 domain and forest functional levels.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Package managers in Linux distributions can search for the *cifs-utils* package.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The package is from the Samba maintainers.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] NSMB (Netsmb and SMBFS) is a family of in-kernel SMB client implementations in BSD operating systems.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It was first contributed to FreeBSD 4.4 by Boris Popov, and is now found in a wide range of other BSD systems including NetBSD and macOS.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The implementations have diverged significantly ever since.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The macOS version of NSMB is notable for its now-common scheme of representing symlinks.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This "Minshall-French" format shows symlinks as textual files with a `.symlink` extension and a `Xsym\n` magic number, always 1067 bytes long.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] This format is also used for storing symlinks on native SMB servers or unsupported filesystems.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Samba supports this format with an `mfsymlink` option.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] NQ is a family of portable SMB client and server implementations developed by Visuality Systems.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The NQ family comprises an embedded SMB stack (written in C), a Pure Java SMB Client, and a storage SMB server implementation.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] All versions support the SMB 3.1.1 dialect.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] They support Linux, Windows CE, iOS, Android, VxWorks and other operating systems.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] MoSMB is a user space SMB implementation for Linux.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Key features include Cloud-scale Active-Active Scale-out Clusters, SMB Direct (RDMA), SMB Multichannel, Transparent Failover and Continuous Availability.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] MoSMB also supports Amazon S3 object storage as storage backend in addition to POSIX file systems such as ext4, ZFS, Lustre, Ceph, etc.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Fusion File Share by Tuxera is a proprietary SMB server implementation developed by Tuxera that can be run either in kernel or user space.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It supports SMB 3.1.1 and all previous versions, additionally advanced SMB features like continuous availability (persistent handles) scale-out, RDMA (SMB Direct), SMB multichannel, transparent compression, shadow copy.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Likewise developed a CIFS/SMB implementation (versions 1.0, 2.0, 2.1 and SMB 3.0) in 2009 that provided a multiprotocol, identity-aware platform for network access to files used in OEM storage products built on Linux/Unix based devices.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] The platform could be used for traditional NAS, Cloud Gateway, and Cloud Caching devices for providing secure access to files across a network.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Likewise was purchased by EMC Isilon in 2012.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] KSMBD is an open source in-kernel CIFS/SMB server implementation for the Linux kernel.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Compared to user-space implementations, it provides better performance and makes it easier to implement some features such as SMB Direct.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] It supports SMB 3.1.1 and previous versions.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Over the years, there have been many security vulnerabilities in Microsoft's implementation of the protocol or components on which it directly relies.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Other vendors' security vulnerabilities lie primarily in a lack of support for newer authentication protocols like NTLMv2 and Kerberos in favor of protocols like NTLMv1, LanMan, or plaintext passwords.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] Real-time attack tracking shows that SMB is one of the primary attack vectors for intrusion attempts, for example the 2014 Sony Pictures attack and the WannaCry ransomware attack of 2017.
[src:aws-fsx/server-message-block] In 2020, two SMB high-severity vulnerabilities were disclosed and dubbed as SMBGhost (CVE-2020-0796) and SMBleed (CVE-2020-1206), which when chained together can provide remote code execution (RCE) privilege to the attacker.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] A "storage system" is also known as a storage array, disk array, or *filer*.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Storage systems typically use special hardware and software along with disk drives in order to provide very fast and reliable storage for computing and data processing.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Storage systems are complex, and may be thought of as a special purpose computer designed to provide storage capacity along with advanced data protection features.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Disk drives are only one element within a storage system, along with hardware and special purpose embedded software within the system.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Storage systems can provide either block accessed storage, or file accessed storage.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Block access is typically delivered over Fibre Channel, iSCSI, SAS, FICON or other protocols.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] File access is often provided using NFS or SMB protocols.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Virtualization of storage helps achieve location independence by abstracting the physical location of the data.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The virtualization system presents to the user a logical space for data storage and handles the process of mapping it to the actual physical location.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It is possible to have multiple layers of virtualization or mapping.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It is then possible that the output of one layer of virtualization can then be used as the input for a higher layer of virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Virtualization maps space between back-end resources, to front-end resources.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In this instance, "back-end" refers to a logical unit number (LUN) that is not presented to a computer, or host system for direct use.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] A "front-end" LUN or volume is presented to a host or computer system for use.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The actual form of the mapping will depend on the chosen implementation.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Some implementations may limit the granularity of the mapping which may limit the capabilities of the device.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Typical granularities range from a single physical disk down to some small subset (multiples of megabytes or gigabytes) of the physical disk.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In a block-based storage environment, a single block of information is addressed using a LUN identifier and an offset within that LUN – known as a logical block addressing (LBA).
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The virtualization software or device is responsible for maintaining a consistent view of all the mapping information for the virtualized storage.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This mapping information is often called metadata and is stored as a mapping table.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The address space may be limited by the capacity needed to maintain the mapping table.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The level of granularity, and the total addressable space both directly impact the size of the meta-data, and hence the mapping table.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] For this reason, it is common to have trade-offs, between the amount of addressable capacity and the granularity or access granularity.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] One common method to address these limits is to use multiple levels of virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In several storage systems deployed today, it is common to utilize three layers of virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Some implementations do not use a mapping table, and instead calculate locations using an algorithm.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] These implementations utilize dynamic methods to calculate the location on access, rather than storing the information in a mapping table.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The virtualization software or device uses the metadata to re-direct I/O requests.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It will receive an incoming I/O request containing information about the location of the data in terms of the logical disk (vdisk) and translates this into a new I/O request to the physical disk location.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Most implementations allow for heterogeneous management of multi-vendor storage devices within the scope of a given implementation's support matrix.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This means that the following capabilities are not limited to a single vendor's device (as with similar capabilities provided by specific storage controllers) and are in fact possible across different vendors' devices.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Data replication techniques are not limited to virtualization appliances and as such are not described here in detail.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] However most implementations will provide some or all of these replication services.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] When storage is virtualized, replication services must be implemented above the software or device that is performing the virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This is true because it is only above the virtualization layer that a true and consistent image of the logical disk (vdisk) can be copied.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This limits the services that some implementations can implement – or makes them seriously difficult to implement.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] If the virtualization is implemented in the network or higher, this renders any replication services provided by the underlying storage controllers useless.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The physical storage resources are aggregated into storage pools, from which the logical storage is created.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] More storage systems, which may be heterogeneous in nature, can be added as and when needed, and the virtual storage space will scale up by the same amount.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This process is fully transparent to the applications using the storage infrastructure.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The software or device providing storage virtualization becomes a common disk manager in the virtualized environment.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Logical disks (vdisks) are created by the virtualization software or device and are mapped (made visible) to the required host or server, thus providing a common place or way for managing all volumes in the environment.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] One of the major benefits of abstracting the host or server from the actual storage is the ability to **migrate** data while maintaining concurrent I/O access.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The host only knows about the logical disk (the mapped LUN) and so any changes to the meta-data mapping is transparent to the host.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This means the actual data can be moved or replicated to another physical location without affecting the operation of any clieaa5c7597941c0c265ff85b 5b2644754c5cbfb8366f89 7ce5bc82f28656e82136nt.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] When the data has been copied or moved, the meta-data can simply be updated to point to the new location, therefore freeing up the physical storage at the old location.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The process of moving the physical location is known as **data migration**.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Most implementations allow for this to be done in a non-disruptive manner, that is concurrently while the host continues to perform I/O to the logical disk (or LUN).
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The mapping granularity dictates how quickly the meta-data can be updated, how much extra capacity is required during the migration, and how quickly the previous location is marked as free.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The smaller the granularity the faster the update, less space required and quicker the old storage can be freed up.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] There are many day to day tasks a storage administrator has to perform that can be simply and concurrently performed using data migration techniques.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Utilization can be increased by virtue of the pooling, migration, and thin provisioning services.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This allows users to avoid over-buying and over-provisioning storage solutions.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In other words, this kind of utilization through a shared pool of storage can be easily and quickly allocated as it is needed to avoid constraints on storage capacity that often hinder application performance.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] When all available storage capacity is pooled, system administrators no longer have to search for disks that have free space to allocate to a particular host or server.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] A new logical disk can be simply allocated from the available pool, or an existing disk can be expanded.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Pooling also means that all the available storage capacity can potentially be used.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In a traditional environment, an entire disk would be mapped to a host.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This may be larger than is required, thus wasting space.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In a virtual environment, the logical disk (LUN) is assigned the capacity required by the using host.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Storage can be assigned where it is needed at that point in time, reducing the need to *guess* how much a given host will need in the future.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Using Thin Provisioning, the administrator can create a very large thin provisioned logical disk, thus the using system thinks it has a very large disk from day one.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] With storage virtualization, multiple independent storage devices, even if scattered across a network, appear to be a single monolithic storage device and can be managed centrally.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] However, traditional storage controller management is still required.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] That is, the creation and maintenance of RAID arrays, including error and fault management.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Once the abstraction layer is in place, only the virtualizer knows where the data actually resides on the physical medium.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Backing out of a virtual storage environment therefore requires the reconstruction of the logical disks as contiguous disks that can be used in a traditional manner.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Most implementations will provide some form of back-out procedure and with the data migration services it is at least possible, but time consuming.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Interoperability is a key enabler to any virtualization software or device.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It applies to the actual physical storage controllers and the hosts, their operating systems, multi-pathing software and connectivity hardware.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Interoperability requirements differ based on the implementation chosen.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] For example, virtualization implemented within a storage controller adds no extra overhead to host based interoperability, but will require additional support of other storage controllers if they are to be virtualized by the same software.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Switch based virtualization may not require specific host interoperability — if it uses packet cracking techniques to redirect the I/O.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Network based appliances have the highest level of interoperability requirements as they have to interoperate with all devices, storage and hosts.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Information is one of the most valuable assets in today's business environments.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Once virtualized, the metadata are the glue in the middle.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] If the metadata are lost, so is all the actual data as it would be virtually impossible to reconstruct the logical drives without the mapping information.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Any implementation must ensure its protection with appropriate levels of back-ups and replicas.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It is important to be able to reconstruct the meta-data in the event of a catastrophic failure.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The metadata management also has implications on performance.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Any virtualization software or device must be able to keep all the copies of the metadata atomic and quickly updateable.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Some implementations restrict the ability to provide certain fast update functions, such as point-in-time copies and caching where super fast updates are required to ensure minimal latency to the actual I/O being performed.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In some implementations the performance of the physical storage can actually be improved, mainly due to caching.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Caching however requires the visibility of the data contained within the I/O request and so is limited to in-band and symmetric virtualization software and devices.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] However these implementations also directly influence the latency of an I/O request (cache miss), due to the I/O having to flow through the software or device.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Assuming the software or device is efficiently designed this impact should be minimal when compared with the latency associated with physical disk accesses.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Due to the nature of virtualization, the mapping of logical to physical requires some processing power and lookup tables.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Therefore, every implementation will add some small amount of latency.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In addition to response time concerns, throughput has to be considered.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The bandwidth into and out of the meta-data lookup software directly impacts the available system bandwidth.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In asymmetric implementations, where the meta-data lookup occurs before the information is read or written, bandwidth is less of a concern as the meta-data are a tiny fraction of the actual I/O size.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In-band, symmetric flow through designs are directly limited by their processing power and connectivity bandwidths.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Most implementations provide some form of scale-out model, where the inclusion of additional software or device instances provides increased scalability and potentially increased bandwidth.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The performance and scalability characteristics are directly influenced by the chosen implementation.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Host-based virtualization requires additional software running on the host, as a privileged task or process.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] In some cases volume management is built into the operating system, and in other instances it is offered as a separate product.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Volumes (LUN's) presented to the host system are handled by a traditional physical device driver.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] However, a software layer (the volume manager) resides above the disk device driver intercepts the I/O requests, and provides the meta-data lookup and I/O mapping.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Most modern operating systems have some form of logical volume management built-in (in Linux called Logical Volume Manager or LVM; in Solaris and FreeBSD, ZFS's zpool layer; in Windows called Logical Disk Manager or LDM), that performs virtualization tasks.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Note: Host based volume managers were in use long before the term *storage virtualization* had been coined.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Like host-based virtualization, several categories have existed for years and have only recently been classified as virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Simple data storage devices, like single hard disk drives, do not provide any virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] But even the simplest disk arrays provide a logical to physical abstraction, as they use RAID schemes to join multiple disks in a single array (and possibly later divide the array it into smaller volumes).
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Advanced disk arrays often feature cloning, snapshots and remote replication.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Generally these devices do not provide the benefits of data migration or replication across heterogeneous storage, as each vendor tends to use their own proprietary protocols.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] A new breed of disk array controllers allows the downstream attachment of other storage devices.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] For the purposes of this article we will only discuss the later style which do actually virtualize other storage devices.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] A primary storage controller provides the services and allows the direct attachment of other storage controllers.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Depending on the implementation these may be from the same or different vendors.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The primary controller will provide the pooling and meta-data management services.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It may also provide replication and migration services across those controllers which it is .
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Storage virtualization operating on a network based device (typically a standard server or smart switch) and using iSCSI or FC Fibre channel networks to connect as a SAN.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] These types of devices are the most commonly available and implemented form of virtualization.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The virtualization device sits in the SAN and provides the layer of abstraction between the hosts performing the I/O and the storage controllers providing the storage capacity.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] There are two commonly available implementations of network-based storage virtualization, appliance-based and switch-based.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Both models can provide the same services, disk management, metadata lookup, data migration and replication.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Both models also require some processing hardware to provide these services.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Appliance based devices are dedicated hardware devices that provide SAN connectivity of one form or another.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] These sit between the hosts and storage and in the case of in-band (symmetric) appliances can provide all of the benefits and services discussed in this article.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] I/O requests are targeted at the appliance itself, which performs the meta-data mapping before redirecting the I/O by sending its own I/O request to the underlying storage.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The in-band appliance can also provide caching of data, and most implementations provide some form of clustering of individual appliances to maintain an atomic view of the metadata as well as cache data.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Switch based devices, as the name suggests, reside in the physical switch hardware used to connect the SAN devices.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] These also sit between the hosts and storage but may use different techniques to provide the metadata mapping, such as packet cracking to snoop on incoming I/O requests and perform the I/O redirection.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It is much more difficult to ensure atomic updates of metadata in a switched environment and services requiring fast updates of data and metadata may be limited in switched implementations.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization is a type of storage virtualization that uses files as the basic unit of storage.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This is in contrast to block-based storage virtualization, which uses blocks as the basic unit.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] It is a way to abstract away the physical details of storage and allow files to be stored on any type of storage device, without the need for specific drivers or other low-level configuration.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization can be used for storage consolidation, improved storage utilization, virtualization and disaster recovery.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] This can simplify storage administration and reduce the overall number of storage devices that need to be managed.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] System administrators and software developers administer the virtual storage through offline operations using built-in or third-party tools.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The virtual disk is implemented as either split over a collection of flat files, typically each one is 2GB in size, collectively called a *split* flat file, or as a single, large *monolithic* flat file.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The pre-allocated storage scheme is also referred to as a *thick provisioning* scheme.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The virtual disk can again be implemented using split or monolithic files, except that storage is allocated on demand.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] Several Virtual Machine Monitor implementations initialize the storage with zeros before providing it to the virtual machine that is in operation.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] The dynamic growth storage scheme is also referred to as a *thin provisioning* scheme.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization can also improve storage utilization by allowing files to be stored on devices that are not being used to their full capacity.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] For example, if a file server has a number of hard drives that are only partially filled, file-based virtualization can be used to store files on those drives, thereby increasing the utilization of the storage devices.
[src:aws-fsx/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization can be used to create a virtual file server (or virtual NAS device), which is a storage system that appears to the user as a single file server but which is actually implemented as a set of files stored on a number of physical file servers.
